content.description: Located on the left-most face of the boulder. Start on a left-hand mantle and right-hand jug. Climb straight up the ledges to a slopey and sketchy top out. The crux is the top out.
content.location: The face with the white splotches in the rock.

content.description: On the corner in between the left and right faces. Double mono start! (Hence the name!) Start with one left finger on a tiny mono crimp left of the corner and one right finger on a slightly better mono pocket in the crack right of the corner. Climb straight up the corner to a slopey top out.
content.location: On the corner where the left and right faces meet each other. It may be hard to see the left mono crimp as it's really small, but the pictures show it well!

content.description: On the right face of the boulder. Start in a squat matching a low obvious crimp. Feet and hands can start left of the crack, but other than the starting holds, the left crack and everything left of it are off. The right crack has enough features (two cool side pulls and a mono pocket) to get to the top that makes the route challenging and fun. Top out on the middle/right of the face.
content.location: The right-most face of the boulder. Two big cracks (but only the right one is on)

content.description: This boulder is about 12' tall and is just south across the rocky beach from the White Sun Boulder. The main bouldering is furthest away from the shore and offers a couple of good problems with some tricky top-outs. The landing is nice and flat but covered with rocks so make sure you bring a couple of pads. All the routes are shaded by the boulder in the afternoon which makes for some better climbing, but if you get too hot, lake superior is just right there!
